Re: ProMED-mail Anaplasmosis, bovine - USA: information 20190603.6500934
------------------------------------------------------------------------
[1]
Date: Mon 3 Jun 2019
From: Susan M Noh <smnoh@wsu.edu> [edited]


Some of the information in the recent posting about bovine anaplasmosis in the USA is inaccurate and incomplete. As a veterinary pathologist who has worked on researching various aspects of bovine anaplasmosis for more than 10 years, I would like to correct a couple of inaccuracies and add my 2 cents worth in regards to the posting from the American Thinker [referenced above].

First, the article confounds 2 different pathogens. _Anaplasma marginale_, causes bovine anaplasmosis referred to as bovine "yellow fever" in the posting. _A. marginale_ does not infect humans. _A. phagocytophilum_ has been detected in cattle, particularly in Europe, but more typically infects small ruminants, horses, and is a human pathogen. In humans the disease caused by _A. phagocytophilum_ is called human granulocytic ehrlichiosis.

Second, _A. marginale_ infects cattle for life, however, many animals remain clinically normal and never develop disease. Thus, serosurveys that detect antibodies to _A. marginale_ give an accurate indication of the prevalence of infection but give no indication of the actual disease burden. Rigorous surveillance programs enumerating the burden of disease and death due to _A. marginale_ are required to fill this critical knowledge gap.

Last, bovine anaplasmosis can present as unexpected death in groups of animals or an occasional sick animal or 2 in a herd. Because _A. marginale_ lives in the red blood cells, the major clinical signs are referable to anemia. In severe cases, the animals may develop icterus, thus the "yellow fever", in other cases the animals do not become icteric. Much of the information concerning bovine anaplasmosis is dated and there is quite a lot of mythology surrounding this disease. It is possible, and perhaps likely, that animals developing icterus are infected with other pathogens or are experiencing stress for other reasons. One important step toward understanding the current disease burden due to bovine anaplasmosis is to do the appropriate diagnostic tests, particularly blood smears.

Blood smears are simple and inexpensive and will help confirm _A. marginale_ as the cause of illness or death because infected red blood cells are numerous and easy to identify in clinical cases of bovine anaplasmosis. In persistently infected animals dying of other causes, infected red blood cells will be much less numerous. Importantly, blood smears will also rule-out the presence of other hemoparasites that can also cause hemolytic crises, which is critically important in understanding our current, dynamic situation and helping come up with solutions to this problem for cattle producers.

--
Susan Noh DVM, PhD, DACVP
USDA-ARS Animal Disease Research Unit
Washington State University
Pullman, WA 99164-6630
USA
<smnoh@wsu.edu>

