[2]
Date: Tue 4 Jun 2019
From: Grant Burcham <gburcham@purdue.edu> [edited]


The cited article authored by Chriss Street and sourced from American Thinker on [3 Jun 2019] regarding bovine anaplasmosis in the United States was riddled with inaccuracies and misleading statements. Importantly, the causative agents of bovine anaplasmosis (_Anaplasma marginale_) and human granulocytic anaplasmosis (_A. phagocytophilum_) are separate organisms, with different biological vectors and different host ranges, and which infect different cell types within the host. _A. marginale_ does not infect humans and does not present risk of spreading to people from cattle, as the article stated. This article implied that the CDC has collected data on bovine anaplasmosis and warned of a "widespread epidemic;" however, the CDC does not collect data or report on diseases solely regarded as veterinary diseases, such as bovine anaplasmosis. In addition, the range of human granulocytic anaplasmosis follows that of its biological vector, _Ixodes scapularis_, which is prevalent mostly in the Northeast, not the litany of states mentioned in the article. Lastly, a statement included by the ProMED moderator implied that ticks were not the most important vectors of anaplasmosis in some locations, suggesting instead that haematophagous flies were to blame. Scoles et al. have published data suggesting that ticks, as compared to biting flies, are much more efficient vectors of bovine anaplasmosis.

The source material for this ProMED post was an online publication known for peddling conspiracy theories and pseudoscience. More care should be taken by ProMED to verify sources and moderate content, in order to decrease the spread of falsehoods regarding medical information.

--
Grant N Burcham (Purdue University), <gburcham@purdue.edu>
G Kenitra Hendrix (Purdue University),
and
Kelly A Brayton (Washington State University)

[I must heartily thank Susan for her informed and authoritative correction. Most appreciated and welcome. I must admit to feeling mildly guilty as I had worked on the disease many years ago but time has dulled my memory for scientific facts. Another lesson to take from this is that not all journals are equally reliable and take note when a report on a livestock disease has a medical public health tag. And remember that diagnoses of cause of death can be confused with chronic infections as death with can be falsely lumped with death from.

And also the Burcham trio for their fair comments. Apropos one of the strengths of ProMED is the willingness of its members to jump in with comments. But while ticks may be more efficient in transmitting this pathogen, you have to have ticks to do it. Thanks to fire ants we lack ticks and so this pathogen has to survive in this part of the US using other methods, one of which are haematophagous flies. - Mod.MHJ

